The paper presents a motion planning algorithm for robots cooperating with humans in a shared workspace, which involves aspects of robotics (cs.RO), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), human-computer interaction (cs.HC), machine learning (cs.LG), and computer vision (cs.CV). The use of offline learning of human actions and their temporal coherence to predict human actions at runtime suggests a strong emphasis on machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The focus on safe trajectories and cooperation with humans suggests a strong emphasis on human-computer interaction (cs.HC). Finally, the use of simulated and real-world scenarios suggests a potential emphasis on computer vision (cs.CV) for perception and sensing.
